# __PROJECT_NAME__

A Cloudflare Worker that fronts an existing **Meter-backed MCP endpoint** with
**OAuth 2.1**, so MCP clients whose remote-connector UX assumes OAuth (claude.ai
custom connectors and the like) can connect with a "Connect" button instead of
custom `x-meter-customer-id` / buyer-token headers.

```text
MCP client ──OAuth──▶ this Worker ──buyer headers──▶ __BACKEND_BASE_URL____MCP_PATH__ ──Meter──▶ credits
                      /mcp (pass-through)
```

## What it is (and is NOT)

- **A thin OAuth + pass-through proxy.** It forwards the JSON-RPC request
  verbatim to your MCP endpoint and injects the buyer identity from the OAuth
  grant. It re-implements no tools and owns no billing, so it can never drift
  from your backend.
- **No compute, no state.** Whatever your MCP endpoint does stays there; this
  Worker only adds OAuth and header injection.

## Backend contract (required)

This Worker expects your service backend (`__BACKEND_BASE_URL__`) to expose:

- `POST /api/meter/customers` → `{ buyerToken }` — provision an anonymous buyer.
- `POST /api/meter/customers/:id/token` → `{ buyerToken, expiresIn }` — re-mint a
  short-lived buyer token, authenticated by the `__BUYER_HEADER__` header.
- Your MCP endpoint at `__MCP_PATH__`, authenticated by `x-meter-customer-id` +
  `__BUYER_HEADER__`, ideally **stateless** (no in-memory MCP sessions).

The `@meter-mcp/cli` scaffolds (the buyer-token helper and these routes) are the
reference implementation; the Liminal and Parallax services use exactly this
shape.

## How identity works

Meter MCP buyers are account-less prepaid credit holders, so the OAuth consent
page (`/authorize`) *is* the identity flow: mint a fresh buyer (credentials are
shown once on an interstitial so the balance is recoverable) or paste an
existing `customerLocalId` + buyer token.

## Revocable spend

The grant stores a **1-hour** buyer token and re-mints it on every OAuth token
exchange; access tokens live 30 min, so a refresh always re-mints while the
current token is valid. Revoking the OAuth grant stops the re-mint, so **spend
halts within one hour**. A transient re-mint failure keeps the existing token so
a backend blip does not disconnect a live client.

## Run / deploy

```bash
npm install
npx wrangler kv namespace create OAUTH_KV     # paste the id into wrangler.jsonc
npm run test
npm run dev                                    # wrangler dev on :8787
npm run deploy
```

Config lives in `wrangler.jsonc` `vars` (`BACKEND_BASE_URL`, `MCP_PATH`,
`BUYER_HEADER`, `SERVICE_NAME`). No secrets: the Worker holds no keys — buyer
tokens are minted by your backend at consent time.
